Fiennes was one of the victims of Jack Cade’s insurrection in June 1450. In the autumn of 1449, discontent with the government was universal, 3ηά when the Commons met on Nov. 6, the popular opinion pointed to Suflolk as the cause of all the national calamities and national disgrace. He and those about him had impoverished the king and enriched themselves The commons on meeting elected Sir John Popham Speaker. The air of Westminster was pestilential, and the first session of the new Parliament was held at the house of the preaching sriars near Ludgate. The House debated public affairs, but there are few records os their doings on the Rolls between the day ol their meeting and Dec. 17, when they were prorogued.
